00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:58.000
And, Edgar, I know you briefly mentioned this towards the beginning,

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:01.000
but this is a common question I've heard from customers,

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:07.000
so I was wondering, can you share a bit more about when to use pins versus database?

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:09.000
Yeah, of course.

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:12.000
The main thing about, like I mentioned during the demo,

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:16.000
is to think in terms of how big your data is and how much of the data you're going to use.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:23.000
If it's really large amounts of data and you're actually only accessing part of it,

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:29.000
you know, this is the sales data, you only want a specific month, a specific range of dates,

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:34.000
you don't want the whole thing, then it makes more sense to use a database

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:37.000
versus a pin where you would download everything.

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:41.000
That, to me, is more about being able to have some ancillary data,

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:45.000
then later it may be kind of promoted into a database.

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:49.000
But there are certain instances where you just want to keep the data in because you've downloaded it

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:53.000
or it changes a lot inside your team.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:07:00.000
Advantages inside the Databricks ecosystem is that it's not a big lift between choosing the two, right?

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:05.000
Because the table is so easy to instantiate, especially if you have the rights to do so,

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:11.000
that it's really more about deciding what the best tool is on small data versus larger data,

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:13.000
or also the object, right?

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:18.000
Because you cannot save a list object to a database unless you want to get complicated.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:21.000
Or a model, for example, like we showed in the demo,

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:25.000
those are more like, you know, objects that are better in a volume,

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:28.000
which you could use pins for.

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:34.000
I know this integration between pins and Databricks is pretty new, like a few months, right?

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:35.000
Yeah.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:38.000
Okay, but how long have you been working on pins?

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:41.000
Oh, man, since it started.

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:46.000
I remember when Javier was talking about it.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:51.000
I know that Tarif, who's the president of the company, was talking about it too before that.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:55.000
So yeah, since the very beginning, I saw the first few drafts of it,

00:07:55.000 --> 00:08:02.000
and I really enjoyed and liked the concept and how we could use boards and pins

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:07.000
and really to get some data easily shared.

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:14.000
Because this has been an issue with, you know, customers or even personally, you know,

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:19.000
when you try to share some data across teams or even across projects,

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:23.000
you have to copy the data over and over again, and you end up with a bunch of versions of it.

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:28.000
It's better that you have something centralized that is also versioned, like we discussed with pins.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:31.000
And that's what I think got me really excited about it.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:32.000
Cool.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:38.000
So I know I've heard back from a few years ago when I used to work in sales,

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:42.000
some customers had some questions around, like, security of pins,

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:45.000
and I was wondering how is that addressed with Databricks?

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:55.000
Yeah, so Databricks has a really good authentication and security infrastructure

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:56.000
that you can use.

00:08:56.000 --> 00:09:00.000
You can lock down to each object.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:05.000
And by object, I mean files, tables, anything that you have inside the Unity catalog.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:12.000
So it's really easy for you to make sure that only folks who are supposed to access it

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:17.000
inside your environment in Databricks can access it.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:22.000
Having said that, of course, any security system is going to be as secure as you make it.

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:27.000
The best example I can give is, like, you could have the best lock in your door,

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:29.000
the most secure lock in your door.

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:32.000
But if you forget to actually turn the key and actually lock it,

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:34.000
it really doesn't do anything for you.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:36.000
So that's the other thing, right?

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:40.000
The infrastructure provided by Databricks will make it secure,

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:47.000
but it's also up to us to make sure that we set up the proper security on top of –

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:53.000
not security, sorry, the proper permissions for the folks that need to access it

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:59.000
actually are able to and those who are not, not.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:00.000
Awesome. Thank you.

