00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:42.000
Another question was, can you suggest some best practices

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:45.000
for troubleshooting the connection to Databricks?

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:49.000
Somebody said, when I try to pin a DataFrame over 1,000 rows

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:52.000
to my Unity catalog, the process hangs and doesn't complete.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:57.000
I'm unsure if it's a limitation on my local machine or my Databricks instance.

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:02.000
That's a great problem to diagnose.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:08.000
So one of the things I would say, I would definitely check to see if,

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:12.000
let's say, like the first 100 hang, right?

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:16.000
And then try the next 200.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:19.000
We may be kind of focusing on rows and not columns.

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:21.000
There may be also an issue that it's very wide,

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:26.000
and it takes a lot of data, a lot of bandwidth.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:29.000
Another problem that you may have is that,

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:33.000
in the serialization of the object, there may be an issue.

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:37.000
So there may be some bad data, right?

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:40.000
And that is not being converted properly, and that's what's hanging.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:43.000
So I would, usually, whenever a customer has this problem,

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:45.000
I suggest that, first of all, you partition the data.

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:49.000
Let's say go 100, then 200, 300, see where it fails,

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:54.000
and see if that, let's say it fails at 500, right?

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:59.000
Then try to upload the number 400 to 500 and see if that fails.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:01.000
Because if that fails, that means there's some issue with your data,

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:03.000
not with the amount.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:07.000
So that's how I would start to diagnose that.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:11.000
I don't know if it's an issue with anything on your local machine,

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:13.000
as far as uploading.

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:16.000
Unless you have a really locked-down machine by your company

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:18.000
where you have to go to a proxy and things like that,

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:20.000
that may be the problem.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:26.000
You should be able to ask the IT security team in your company

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:28.000
to see if there's any limitations on that proxy,

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:31.000
if you're going through that as well.

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:33.000
Great. Thank you.

