00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:16.000
We see some folks on RStudio, some folks on Positron now,

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:19.000
especially when it comes to Databricks and folks like Notebook.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:24.000
So it's really rare now to see a homogenous implementation,

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:26.000
the same exact IDE across all teams.

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:30.000
That's one reason too, and not to get too commercial about it,

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:33.000
but that's why Posit Workbench exists.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:37.000
And we acknowledge the fact that that doesn't happen anymore, right?

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:42.000
Because we want to make sure that you're successful,

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:44.000
as successful as possible.

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:48.000
And that usually means too, giving you the best runway

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:50.000
for you to be able to do whatever you need,

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:54.000
which means also having an IDE that you feel comfortable in.

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:58.000
Great. Thank you, Edgar.

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:02.000
So I know you've worked on a ton of front packages as well.

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:04.000
So if people had other questions

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:08.000
that weren't specific to Databricks and pins,

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:12.000
what are things that you're excited to talk about?

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:15.000
Oh, wow.

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:19.000
Right now, this whole thing with the LLMs and AI,

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:21.000
it's pretty exciting.

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:24.000
Not so much from the coding assistant part

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:29.000
that I think most of us have kind of tied AI to,

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:31.000
but more on the data side.

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:34.000
I feel like there's a lot of opportunity there.

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:36.000
I've been working on a package called mall

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:44.000
that lets you run role-wise and check to see,

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:46.000
let's say, if you want to run an LLP operation,

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:48.000
like sentiment analysis,

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:50.000
instead of you having to spend a lot of time

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:53.000
training a sentiment NLP,

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:56.000
you can use an LLM to basically determine for you

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:59.000
if it's positive or negative or neutral.

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:03.000
So it's really easy for you to run those analysis using that.

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:06.000
So I feel like that's very exciting for me.

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:08.000
We also have the lang package.

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:10.000
It's a nascent package,

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:15.000
but it translates our help into a different human language,

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:19.000
like from English to Spanish or French.

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:22.000
So to make it easier for us to be able to,

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:25.000
because English is my second language,

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:28.000
to make it easier for us to kind of read the help

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:29.000
in our own language.

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:31.000
And the LLM does a great job,

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:32.000
especially the modern ones,

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:35.000
that I feel like that implementation of it

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:39.000
is really exciting to kind of look at the possibilities for it.

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:40.000
Thank you.

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:43.000
I don't think I heard of that second one, lang, yet,

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:46.000
